        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(infra): bound jsonl-socket response buffer to prevent OOM",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\r\n\r\n`requestJsonlSocket` accumulates all incoming socket data into an unbounded string buffer until a newline is seen or the socket closes. A buggy or hostile peer that streams data without newlines can force the runtime to keep buffering until timeout or OOM. This is the same class of boundary issue fixed for provider response reads by Alix-007 in #96903, #96886, etc.\r\n\r\n## Changes\r\n\r\n- `src/infra/jsonl-socket.ts`: added `JSONL_SOCKET_MAX_BUFFER_BYTES = 1 * 1024 * 1024`. The `data` handler now checks the buffer byte length after each chunk and returns `null` early when the cap is exceeded, destroying the socket. 1 MiB was chosen because this is a local control-plane JSONL channel (exec-approvals / exec-host) and the project already uses 1 MiB caps for similar small-payload boundaries (e.g., `DEFAULT_MAX_FILE_BYTES`, `MAX_PROPOSAL_DRAFT_BYTES`).\r\n- `src/infra/jsonl-socket.test.ts`: added a regression test that streams a newline-free body larger than the cap and asserts `requestJsonlSocket` resolves to `null`.\r\n\r\n## Real behavior proof\r\n\r\n- **Behavior addressed**: A peer streaming a newline-free body larger than the cap must not hang or grow memory until timeout; the call must return `null` quickly.\r\n- **Real environment tested**: Local Node v22 workspace, real `net.createServer` / `net.Socket` over a Unix domain socket in `/tmp`.\r\n- **Exact steps**: `node --import tsx /tmp/proof-jsonl-socket.mts` starts a server that streams 64 KiB chunks every 5 ms with no newline, then calls `requestJsonlSocket` with a 2 s timeout.\r\n- **Observed result after fix**: `RESULT: result=null elapsedMs=104`. Before the fix the same script waited for the full timeout: `RESULT: result=null elapsedMs=2016`.\r\n- **What was not tested**: Live exec-approvals / exec-host daemons were not exercised; the proof uses the exact exported function and a real socket, and the in-repo Vitest regression locks the cap behavior.\r\n\r\n## Evidence\r\n\r\nTerminal proof (real socket, streaming peer without newlines):\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ node --import tsx /tmp/proof-jsonl-socket.mts\r\nRESULT: result=null elapsedMs=104\r\n```\r\n\r\nNegative control (temporary revert to `origin/main`):\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ git checkout origin/main -- src/infra/jsonl-socket.ts\r\n$ node --import tsx /tmp/proof-jsonl-socket.mts\r\nRESULT: result=null elapsedMs=2016\r\n$ git checkout HEAD -- src/infra/jsonl-socket.ts\r\n```\r\n\r\nFocused Vitest:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/infra/jsonl-socket.test.ts --run\r\n\r\nTest Files  1 passed (1)\r\n      Tests  6 passed (6)\r\n   Duration  441ms\r\n```\r\n\r\nType checks:\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ pnpm tsgo:core      # exit 0\r\n$ pnpm tsgo:core:test # exit 0\r\n```\r\n\r\n",
        "branch": "fix/jsonl-socket-buffer-bound",
